text: I know a few friends have some reservations over Nigel Farage politically, but I will always respect him heavily just because of how ridiculously good he is at surviving. Made it out of a car sabotage assassination attempt and a literal plane crash and just walked away from both.

He's just the type of guy to survive a Titanic type ship sinking or a Trans-Siberian Railway train derailment by building an improvised igloo and drinking an entire bottle of whiskey to warm himself inside while waiting for help to arrive. You just can't fake that type of skills.
Hope to one day have a pint with him cheers

Genuinely can be terrifying. My uncle was a sailor & fisherman all his life spent on the sea and one time a current pulled him in when he was swimming, he could do nothing but just float on his back, the sea moved him for a few hours and threw him out on another beach miles away

Tendons and bones are guided and altered in their development by pressure andtension. Histologists have said they candistinguish structural differences in the bones ofwild and tame animals of the same species, apparently resulting from the differences in their way of life -RP
Coconut oil and gelatin and orange juice
Something ironic in how the only spiritualist/paranormal concepts generally palatable to normies are precisely the indefensibly anti-metaphysical ones like "reincarnation"/metempsychosis.

All of these are just functional vocations with obvious benefit for society. You get to meet a shepherd on occasion, hickchud hunter roofer who raises goats, forester, etc. There's a peace of mind in understanding what everyone around you does, like sleeping behind a locked door.

Traveling is refreshing because you get to see a lot of people with real jobs. Like the mountain lodge keeper chopping wood for the furnace and managing the blankets. Cook. Chairlift operator who straps passengers into the seats and gives them a push at the start. Mountain guide.

Just total dedication to his craft. Doing an exercise system he invented on his own to train around injuries. No way to make money out of it or compete, but just total dedication to it for its own sake until the entire world cannot help but notice it and come to him, in his town.

That Martins Licis video with Kyriakos Grizzly is wonderful where he's talking about how he worked 20 years or so as a night shift factory nightguard and afterwards in the early morning he would drive to the gym and do 4 hours of pushing and pulling a weights sled back and forth.
